# 4. VI Editor Modes

This is the most important VI concept.

VI mainly works using different modes.

For beginners, focus on:

```text id="dt7c6g"
1. Normal Mode
2. Insert Mode
3. Command-Line Mode
```

Some documentation calls Normal Mode "Command Mode."

---

# VI Mode Flow

```text id="pz33u1"
              Open File
                  ↓
            NORMAL MODE
             ↙         ↘
          i, a, o       :
            ↓           ↓
       INSERT MODE   COMMAND-LINE MODE
            ↓           ↓
           Esc      Enter / command result
            ↓           ↓
            └────→ NORMAL MODE
```

The biggest beginner mistake is typing without knowing which mode is active.

Always ask yourself:

```text id="5p6cfh"
Which mode am I in?
```

---

# 5. Normal Mode

When you open a file:

```bash id="27i27n"
vi file.txt
```

you normally start in Normal Mode.

In Normal Mode, keys perform editor actions.

Examples:

```text id="bldlbm"
i   → Enter Insert Mode

x   → Delete character

dd  → Delete line

yy  → Copy line

p   → Paste

u   → Undo

/   → Search forward

:   → Enter Command-Line Mode
```

Important:

If you type:

```text id="13l6e0"
hello
```

while in Normal Mode, VI may interpret those letters as commands instead of inserting the word `hello`.

