# 17. Search and Replace

This is important but potentially dangerous.

Always understand the scope before replacing text.

---

## Replace First Match on Current Line

```text id="e91hhc"
:s/old/new/
```

Example:

```text id="1iw4kq"
:s/8080/9090/
```

This replaces the first match on the current line.

---

## Replace All Matches on Current Line

```text id="sjtns2"
:s/old/new/g
```

The `g` means all matches on that line.

---

## Replace First Match on Every Line

```text id="zfh7uk"
:%s/old/new/
```

---

## Replace All Matches in the Entire File

```text id="rxr8cw"
:%s/old/new/g
```

Example:

```text id="n9b5uj"
:%s/localhost/dbserver/g
```

---

## Replace with Confirmation

```text id="oh24l3"
:%s/old/new/gc
```

The `c` asks for confirmation.

This is safer for important files.

Typical choices include:

```text id="y54kx7"
y → Replace this match

n → Skip this match

a → Replace all remaining matches

q → Quit substitution

l → Replace this match and stop
```

Available choices can vary slightly by implementation.

