# 🧑‍💻 PSA Real-Time Scenario 4 – Replace an Endpoint Carefully

Suppose an approved change requires replacing:

```text id="83umc4"
old-api.internal
```

with:

```text id="5wzyzq"
new-api.internal
```

First inspect occurrences outside the editor:

```bash id="5ibipb"
grep -nF "old-api.internal" application.conf
```

Open:

```bash id="9fhbkv"
vi application.conf
```

Use confirmation:

```text id="bg7rkn"
:%s/old-api\.internal/new-api.internal/gc
```

Why escape the dots?

In regular expressions:

```text id="a3m0i3"
.
```

means any single character.

Escaping:

```text id="19dg1q"
\.
```

means a literal dot.

For simple substitutions, understanding regex behavior prevents accidental replacements.

